		<header>
			
			<h1>Decision time pending in Pacific–EU EPA negotiations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 September 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At a meeting of Pacific ACP (PACP) trade ministers in August 2012, Tuiloma Neroni Slade, Secretary General of the Pacific Forum, noted the ‘high expectations’ the region had of the EPA process and expressed the hope that a final agreement would ‘take into account the specific, special economic, social, environmental and structural constraints of the Pacific ACP states, as well as their capacity to adapt their economies to increased trade with the European Union’. Efforts continued, he said, ‘to negotiate an EPA that is economically meaningful, politically sustainable and socially acceptable’.</p><p>Mr Slade highlighted that the Solomon Islands and the Republic of the Marshall Islands ‘have indicated that they are ready to submit their offers to the EC’, bringing the total to ‘12 Pacific ACP states that have submitted their offers to the EU’. According to Mr Slade, ‘the next negotiating session with the EU, planned for October, will be the critical negotiating session that will determine whether the region will be able to conclude the negotiations this year, or even in the near future.’ He called on regional leaders to recommit to negotiations as a single region and ‘impress on Europe the importance of refocusing the EPA negotiations on the development dimension, taking into account the special circumstances of the Pacific ACP countries’.</p><p>The Tongan prime minister for his part called on Pacific Island governments ‘to reach beyond their narrow national interests, and embrace their collective responsibility to each other when negotiating the Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA)’, while the Tongan minister acting as lead spokesperson for the PACP recognised that ‘there is considerable contention against and between the EC and the ACP over the progress of the EPA negotiations.’</p><p>The process is under way to obtain ministerial endorsement of the region’s negotiating positions for the October 2012 negotiating session.</p><p>The current import restrictions on exports of the regional kava crop to Germany also continue to be of concern to the region’s governments as they consider trade agreements in the context of market access and the broader development dimension. In June 2012, a resolution was adopted at the ACP Council of Ministers meeting in Vanuatu calling on the EC to take a more active role in resolving the kava dispute. The resolution called on the EU to help the ACP countries concerned ‘to engage in an appropriate exchange of views with the authorities of the countries that have banned the import of kava’ and called on the EC to ‘use its good office[s] to facilitate the consultation process’. In the case of no irrefutable evidence justifying the ban being provided by the end of consultations, the resolution called for the immediate removal of import restrictions. It also called for development assistance in promoting the economically sustainable production of kava in the ACP.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Forum Secretariat, ‘The Pacific trade and development nexus’, press release, 16 August 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.forumsec.org/pages.cfm/newsroom/press-statements/2012/pacific-trade-development-nexus.html" target="_self">http://www.forumsec.org/pages.cfm/newsroom/press-statements/2012/pacific...</a></p><p>Forum Secretariat, ‘PACP Trade Ministers urged to consider the region in EPA negotiations’, press release no. 95/12, 16 August 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.forumsec.org/pages.cfm/newsroom/press-statements/2012/pacp-trade-ministers-urged-to-consider-region-in-epa-negotiations.html" target="_self">http://www.forumsec.org/pages.cfm/newsroom/press-statements/2012/pacp-tr...</a></p><p>ACP, ‘Decisions and resolutions of the 95th session of the ACP Council of Ministers held in Port Vila (Vanuatu) from 10 to 15 June 2012: Kava’, ACP/25/2006/12 final version, pp. 23–25 of PDF, 13 June 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp.int/sites/acpsec.waw.be/files/ACP25006%2012%20ENG.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp.int/sites/acpsec.waw.be/files/ACP25006%2012%20ENG.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Calls for PACP governments to ‘reach beyond their narrow national interests and embrace their collective responsibility to each other’ would appear to be directed at Fiji and Papua New Guinea (PNG), both of which have signed an interim EPA (IEPA) but both of which remain participants in the ongoing negotiations for a comprehensive EPA. Both governments have repeatedly expressed in formal meetings their commitment to the ongoing regional negotiation process, in line with the regional mandate endorsed by PACP country leaders. The governments of both Fiji and PNG support the extension of global sourcing under the fisheries rules of origin to fresh, chilled and frozen fish through the comprehensive EPA process. The government of Fiji also sees a comprehensive EPA as a means of relieving some of the restrictions it sees contained in the IEPA.</p><p>The calls by the Tongan PM may in part be seen as reflecting the apparent malaise that seems to be holding back the conclusion of the EPA negotiation process, with little visible progress on substantive issues of concern to PACP governments. This may be linked to a negotiating approach that holds that ‘nothing is agreed until everything is agreed’.</p><p>With regard to the kava issue, ensuring that the EPA provides a framework for addressing SPS and food safety-related issues, which are increasingly the main barrier to exports of ACP food and agricultural products, can be seen as one of the wider 'development friendly' aspects which PACP negotiators want to see integrated into the EPA.</p>
		</div>
		
